    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>You can add a jar in Eclipse by right-clicking on the Project → Build Path → Configure Build Path. Under Libraries tab, click Add Jars or Add External JARs and give the Jar. A quick demo <a href=\"http://tech.bragboy.com/2016/01/quick-way-to-import-jar-in-eclipse.html\" rel=\"noreferrer\">here</a>.</p>\n\n<p><img src=\"https://i.sstatic.net/A6xgq.png\" alt=\"enter image description here\"></p>\n\n<p>The above solution is obviously a \"Quick\" one. However, if you are working on a project where you need to commit files to the source control repository, I would recommend adding Jar files to a dedicated library folder within your source control repository and referencing few or all of them as mentioned above.</p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 69815,
      "reputation" : 9812,
      "user_id" : 202940,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "accept_rate" : 75,
      "profile_image" : "https://i.sstatic.net/JNQ86.jpg?s=256",
      "display_name" : "Ashraf Bashir",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/202940/ashraf-bashir"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 11,
    "last_activity_date" : 1381262238,
    "last_edit_date" : 1381262238,
    "creation_date" : 1279537199,
    "answer_id" : 3280445,
    "question_id" : 3280353,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>Here are the steps:</p>\n\n<ol>\n<li><p>click File > Import. The Import window opens.</p></li>\n<li><p>Under Select an import source, click J2EE > App Client JAR file.</p></li>\n<li><p>Click Next.</p></li>\n<li><p>In the Application Client file field, enter the location and name of the application client JAR file that you want to import. You can click the Browse button to select the JAR file from the file system.</p></li>\n<li><p>In the Application Client project field, type a new project name or select an application client project from the drop-down list. If you type a new name in this field, the application client project will be created based on the version of the application client JAR file, and it will use the default location.</p></li>\n<li><p>In the Target runtime drop-down list, select the application server that you want to target for your development. This selection affects the run time settings by modifying the class path entries for the project.</p></li>\n<li><p>If you want to add the new module to an enterprise application project, select the Add project to an EAR check box and then select an existing enterprise application project from the list or create a new one by clicking New.</p>\n\n<p><strong>Note</strong>: If you type a new enterprise application project name, the enterprise application project will be created in the default location with the lowest compatible J2EE version based on the version of the project being created. If you want to specify a different version or a different location for the enterprise application, you must use the New Enterprise Application Project wizard.</p></li>\n<li><p>Click Finish to import the application client JAR file.</p></li>\n</ol>\n"
  }, {
